        <!-- SECTION 4: The structural difference — no margin call            -->
        <!-- The single most important structural feature. Why CeFi BTC      -->
        <!-- loans aren't the precedent reader expects.                       -->
        <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
        <div class="section">
            <h3>The structural difference: no margin call</h3>
            <p class="prose">Unlike CeFi BTC-backed loans, which liquidate on price (typical 75&ndash;90% LTV trigger), <strong>this product has no price-based margin call at any drawdown level</strong>. The only liquidation trigger is <strong>60 days of payment delinquency on the mortgage</strong>. As long as you make the monthly payments, the pledged collateral sits untouched regardless of where bitcoin&rsquo;s price goes. <em>Your liquidation risk is now driven by your ability to make monthly mortgage payments, not by bitcoin&rsquo;s drawdown profile.</em></p>
        </div>


        <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
        <!-- SECTION 5: The three pledge advantages                           -->
        <!-- The fiscal/operational benefits of pledging vs selling.         -->
        <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
        <div class="section">
            <h3>Three advantages of pledging bitcoin collateral instead of selling bitcoin</h3>
            <p class="prose">The fiscal mechanics behind why a bitcoiner would prefer this product to selling for a down payment break down into three distinct benefits.</p>

            <div class="bbm-advantages">
                <div class="bbm-advantage">
                    <div class="bbm-advantage-num">01</div>
                    <div class="bbm-advantage-title">Stack integrity</div>
                    <p>Your stack is preserved. Selling 1 BTC at today&rsquo;s price to fund a down payment trades that 1 BTC&rsquo;s entire future trajectory &mdash; including the long-duration Power Law trend &mdash; for the immediate fiat amount. Pledging it instead keeps that coin in your stack, compounding for you, while still funding the down payment.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="bbm-advantage">
                    <div class="bbm-advantage-num">02</div>
                    <div class="bbm-advantage-title">Tax deferral</div>
                    <p>Selling triggers a capital-gains event &mdash; up to 20% federal LTCG plus any state tax. Pledging is a loan against the asset, not a disposition, and so the tax liability stays attached to the asset at its original basis. The gain only realizes if and when you actually sell.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="bbm-advantage">
                    <div class="bbm-advantage-num">03</div>
                    <div class="bbm-advantage-title">Yield offsetting</div>
                    <p>If the collateral pledged is a PPSI-designated stablecoin (USDC under the GENIUS Act) rather than bitcoin, the holder can in many configurations continue to earn yield on the pledged balance &mdash; partially offsetting the mortgage interest. The economics there depend on platform-specific terms.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>


        <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
        <!-- SECTION 6: The compliance reality                                -->
        <!-- The tax tracing rules, the deduction limits.                    -->
        <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
        <div class="section">
            <h3>The compliance reality</h3>
            <p class="prose">Standard mortgage compliance applies, plus the IRS requires loan-tracing documentation for the second-lien proceeds (which the servicer provides as part of normal onboarding). The structure is specifically designed to avoid constructive-sale treatment under &sect;1259 of the IRS code: no mandatory price-based hedges, no market-driven liquidations, no margin call. Your accountant and the servicer cover the compliance work &mdash; <em>it&rsquo;s routine, not specialized</em>. The bitcoin-collateral piece doesn&rsquo;t meaningfully increase paperwork beyond what a conventional second-mortgage borrower already does.</p>
        </div>


        <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
        <!-- SECTION 7: Counterparty risk                                    -->
        <!-- The three-counterparty default scenarios, structurally framed.   -->
        <!-- Added during the source-verification pass: the prior decade's    -->
        <!-- CeFi failures live in reader memory; the BBM product's           -->
        <!-- structural differences need explicit framing.                    -->
        <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
        <div class="section">
            <h3>What about counterparty risk?</h3>

            <p class="prose">The 250% over-collateralization and segregated-account custody framework substantially reduce, but don&rsquo;t eliminate, counterparty risk on the pledged bitcoin. Three distinct counterparties hold the structure together, and the failure mode of each is structurally different from the prior decade&rsquo;s CeFi precedents.</p>

            <div class="bbm-roles">
                <div class="bbm-role">
                    <div class="bbm-role-name">Better counterparty risk</div>
                    <p>Better Home &amp; Finance services the loan. If Better failed as an entity, loan servicing typically transfers to another Fannie Mae-approved servicer &mdash; the conforming-mortgage market handles servicing transfers as routine. Loan terms don&rsquo;t change; the borrower keeps making payments to whoever the new servicer is. The conforming-loan wrapper is precisely what makes this routine.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="bbm-role">
                    <div class="bbm-role-name">Coinbase counterparty risk</div>
                    <p>Coinbase Prime custodies the pledged collateral. <em>The custody is segregated, non-rehypothecating</em> &mdash; the same framework used by ETF issuers and public-company treasuries. A Coinbase bankruptcy would put the pledged collateral into bankruptcy-court process, but segregated custody is the structural feature that distinguishes this from Celsius / BlockFi, where commingled and rehypothecated collateral became harder to recover from the estate.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="bbm-role">
                    <div class="bbm-role-name">Fannie Mae counterparty risk</div>
                    <p>Fannie Mae stands behind the primary mortgage as the GSE wrapper. The GSE is in federal conservatorship under FHFA oversight and has had implicit government backing throughout that period. If Fannie Mae&rsquo;s wrapper around conforming mortgages were to materially change, it would change for the whole US conforming-loan market &mdash; not specifically for the bitcoin-backed product.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <p class="prose">The structural advantage versus the prior decade of CeFi bitcoin-backed lending isn&rsquo;t that counterparty risk has been eliminated &mdash; it&rsquo;s that the custody framework is built around segregation rather than commingling, the servicer sits inside a federally regulated mortgage-servicing industry rather than an unregulated lending platform, and the collateral mechanism explicitly excludes rehypothecation. <em>The failure mode that defined the prior decade &mdash; force-liquidation or loss of segregated-but-actually-commingled collateral &mdash; isn&rsquo;t the failure mode of this structure.</em></p>
        </div>



