        <!-- SECTION 9: Connection back to the broader argument               -->
        <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
        <div class="section">
            <h3>How this fits inside the broader argument</h3>

            <p class="prose">The case for pledging instead of selling is, at root, the case for <em>not</em> trading bitcoin&rsquo;s long-duration appreciation for a one-time fiat outlay. If you believe bitcoin&rsquo;s compound annual growth rate over the duration of a 30-year mortgage will exceed your cost of debt &mdash; the central Power Law claim &mdash; then every coin sold today is a coin compounding for someone else, instead of for you. <strong>The bitcoin-backed mortgage exists because that case held up structurally for years but had no regulated vehicle to express it</strong>; the Fannie-Mae-conforming product is the first one that does, with the additional feature of removing margin-call risk from the mechanic.</p>

            <p class="prose">The full hierarchy of bitcoin-backed lending categories sits on the <a href="/borrowing-against-your-stack.html">Borrowing Against Your Stack</a> page. Mortgages sit on the &ldquo;serious consideration&rdquo; tier alongside collaborative-custody multisig and Tier-1 non-rehypothecating CeFi.</p>

            <p class="prose">However, the above seeming benefits do not come without cost. <strong>The principal cost is counterparty risk at three layers &mdash; Fannie Mae, Better Home &amp; Finance, and Coinbase Prime</strong> &mdash; each manageable in isolation but cumulatively a real exposure that simply not taking the loan would avoid entirely (see <em>What about counterparty risk?</em> earlier on this page). The product also requires <strong>2.5&times; over-collateralization</strong> of the pledged stack &mdash; atypical for traditional secured loans, where the loan-to-value on the underlying asset typically runs 80% or higher &mdash; and locks up bitcoin for as long as the second-lien remains outstanding <em>(short of retiring the lien early, subject to any defined costs)</em>. <em>The honest comparison isn&rsquo;t only against the sell path; it&rsquo;s also against the borrow-nothing path</em>, which carries neither of these costs.</p>

            <p class="prose">What the product brings in return is <strong>a rate that, while higher than a vanilla 30-year mortgage, is materially lower than the closest bitcoin-collateralized alternatives, and a scenario that can be argued to be more advantageous over the long term vs. selling bitcoin outright to fund the down-payment</strong>. Collaborative-custody multisig BTC loans typically run 12&ndash;16% APR; Strike&rsquo;s bitcoin-backed loans run roughly 7.5&ndash;10.5% APR depending on loan size; this product runs the standard 30-year rate plus 0.5 to 1.5pp &mdash; regularly the lowest-priced offering in the no-rehypothecation tier.</p>

            <p class="prose">As with the rest of the site, the right reading isn&rsquo;t &ldquo;this is the answer.&rdquo; The right reading is: <em>here&rsquo;s the structural detail you need to evaluate whether it&rsquo;s the answer for your specific situation</em>. If the structural fit lines up and the costs above are ones you&rsquo;ve weighed honestly, this is the cleanest version of the borrow-against-bitcoin approach currently available in the US regulated tier for funding a home purchase. If it doesn&rsquo;t, the page has done its job by helping you walk away on reflection.</p>

            <!-- ─── Math & methodology appendix (collapsed by default) ─── -->
            <details class="bbm-math-collapsible">
                <summary class="bbm-math-summary">Math &amp; methodology &mdash; click to expand the full derivations behind the calculator</summary>
                <div class="bbm-math">
                <p><strong>Inputs.</strong> Home price, down payment percent, BTC stack, current BTC price, cost basis per BTC, conventional 30-year mortgage rate, combined-product premium above conventional, horizon in years, early-repayment year, capital gains tax rate. Stack and current price persist via <code>localStorage</code> across the Borrowing Against Your Stack page so a configured scenario carries between the two pages.</p>
                <p><strong>Pledge path feasibility.</strong> The product requires $2.50 of pledged bitcoin per $1.00 of down-payment credit (a 40% LTV on the pledged stack). When the current stack value at the input price is below the required collateral, the pledge path is flagged not feasible and the calculator surfaces the shortfall instead of producing comparison numbers.</p>
                <p><strong>Pledge path cost differential.</strong> <code>cost(t) = (downPayment &times; rate + homePrice &times; premium) &times; min(t, repayYear)</code>. The two terms decompose as: (a) <em>base-rate interest on the down-payment portion</em> &mdash; the sell path doesn&rsquo;t borrow this amount at all, so doesn&rsquo;t pay any interest on it; (b) <em>the premium applied to the full mortgage</em> &mdash; per Coinbase&rsquo;s product blog, both loans share the combined rate, so the premium applies to the entire borrowed amount, not only the second-lien. Simple-interest approximation; matches the parent BvS calculator&rsquo;s convention and slightly overstates the true cost in an amortizing loan. Early-repayment caps the accrual at <code>repayYear</code>; cost contributions stop after that year (released collateral funds the rest from the borrower&rsquo;s cash flow or via primary refinance to a standard-rate mortgage).</p>
                <p><strong>Pledge path wealth at year t.</strong> <code>stack &times; P<sub>powerLaw</sub>(t) &minus; cost(t)</code>.</p>
                <p><strong>Sell path wealth at year t.</strong> <code>(stack &minus; btcSold) &times; P<sub>powerLaw</sub>(t)</code>, where <code>btcSold = downPayment / (price &minus; taxRate &times; max(0, price &minus; costBasis))</code>. Capital gains tax is treated as an upfront one-time cost embedded in the BTC-sold figure. If the calculation requires selling more BTC than the stack holds, the sell path is flagged not feasible rather than producing a negative quantity.</p>
                <p><strong>Hold (0%) baseline.</strong> <code>stack &times; P<sub>powerLaw</sub>(t)</code> &mdash; no home purchase, no loan, no tax event. Plotted as a dashed reference line on the chart. Both Pledge and Sell are decisions to commit BTC to a home purchase; the gap between either purchase line and the Hold baseline is the <em>all-in cost of acquiring the home at all</em>, against which the Pledge vs Sell comparison is the second-order decision.</p>
                <p><strong>Future BTC price.</strong> Drawn from the Power Law trend <code>P(d) = 1.6 &times; 10<sup>&minus;17</sup> &times; d<sup>5.77</sup></code>, with <code>d</code> measured in days since the bitcoin genesis block (January 3, 2009). These are the canonical coefficients used across the site &mdash; the trajectory matches what the <a href="/the-power-law.html"><em>The Power Law</em></a> page describes and what every other calculator on the site projects against.</p>
                <p><strong>What cancels out (and what doesn&rsquo;t).</strong> The home itself cancels &mdash; both purchase paths buy the same home for the same price, capture the same home appreciation, and accumulate the same home equity. What <em>doesn&rsquo;t</em> cancel: (a) total interest paid on the mortgage (different rates and different principal amounts under the two paths); (b) BTC retained vs sold; (c) the one-time capital gains event under the Sell path. The cost-differential formula above captures (a) at the simple-interest tier. Pre-tax of the mortgage-interest deduction.</p>
                <p><strong>Crossover detection.</strong> The chart marks the year (if any) at which the wealthier purchase path flips from one to the other inside the chosen horizon, computed by linear interpolation between yearly samples. Pledge starts ahead at <code>t=0</code> by the value of unsold BTC; the cumulative cost differential can pull it below the Sell path over time if bitcoin&rsquo;s realized trajectory underperforms the Power Law trend or if the combined premium is large. Early-repayment caps the cost accrual and is a structural lever for keeping Pledge ahead under shorter horizons.</p>
                <p><strong>Historical safety.</strong> Bitcoin has experienced multiple peak-to-trough drawdowns exceeding 70% over the last decade, and many 60-day windows in which price has fallen below 40% of a prior collateral peak. Under the prior decade&rsquo;s CeFi BTC-backed loans, those drawdowns would have triggered immediate force-liquidation by LTV threshold. Under the Fannie-Mae-conforming structure, none of them would have &mdash; the only liquidation trigger is 60-day payment delinquency, not price. The calculator doesn&rsquo;t need a separate &ldquo;was I safe historically&rdquo; surface because under this product structure the answer is the same regardless of historical path: yes, as long as the monthly payment was made.</p>
                </div>
            </details>
        </div>

